<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Launch Electric Train Service in Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 9 (Xinhua) --The Bangladeshi government
decided to build electric trains service in Dhaka, in a bid to
ease the traffic jams in the capital city, sources in the
communication ministry said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said a 51-kilometer single-rail track will be built
on iron frames up to 60 feet high which will connect all the
important points of the capital at a cost of 600 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has floated international tender, seeking
financial and technical assistance for building the railway track.
</P>
<P>
"The response from foreign investors are encouraging," Karar
Mahmudul Hasan, a top official in the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The government would sign an agreement to this effect and
construction will take five years. The foreign contractor would
run the train service for 25 years under the agreement before
handing it over to the government.
</P>
<P>
The government is also implementing a World-Bank funded
environment-friendly and cost-effective transport options for the
9 million dwellers of the capital city which is very often hit by
traffic jams. 
</P>
</TEXT>
