<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Emirates Internet Association (EIA) in the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) and the Acer Computer Group announced a
support sponsor agreement on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The deal was aimed to promote the use of the Internet in the UAE
and to help its integration into the nation's education system.
</P>
<P>
The EIA, set up in June, is the first of its kind in the UAE to
promote the use of the Internet among individuals and corporations.
</P>
<P>
Acer's involvement in the capacity of a support sponsor in this
pro-active initiative by the EIA is in accordance with the
company's corporation strategy, according to a statement issued by
P. Narayanan, regional manager of Acer Computers.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Dubai Financial Market has granted "investor
numbers" to around 350 expatriates living in the United Arab
Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
The "investor number" is an essential prerequisite that allows
foreign investors to own shares in UAE companies, the official WAM
news agency reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mrket analysts estimated that the total of investor number is
now standing at 450-500.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- ADMA OPCO, an affiliate of the Abu Dhabi National
Oil Company (ADNOC), signed an offshore procurement and
construction contract for Khuff Gas Project with the U.S.-based ABB
Lummus and the National Petroleum Construction Company (NPCC).
</P>
<P>
The deal involves the installation of a new gas gathering
network and gas processing platform to enhance ADMA OPCO's
production capacity to 12.15 million cubic meters per day from its
current 8.1 million cubic meters daily.
</P>
<P>
ADMA OPCO also signed another contract with Foster Wheeler
company to provide management consultative services for the
project.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Petroleum Minister of the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) Obeid Bin Saif al Nasir said that the country's new
production quota will be 2.29 million barrels per day (bpd) after
OPEC members agreed Sunday to increase their oil production by 800,
000 bpd.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the UAE will add about 70,000 bpd to its
current output of 2.219 million bpd from October 1.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries hopes oil
prices in the world market to stabilize at 22-28 U.S. dollars per
barrel, said the minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
