<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Economic Czars Convene to Tackle Economy Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Turkish State Minister Recep
Onal said Sunday that strict monetary and financing policies, as
well as structural reforms, should be implemented simultaneously,
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
While addressing a three-day conference, which opened Sunday in
Kemer town of southern Antalya province, Onal said that such moves
are imperative for dropping the medium-term inflation and keeping
on track macro-economic stability.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, termed as the "Second Economic Summit" by local
press, senior Turkish officials in charge of economic affairs will
evaluate overall Turkish economy and put forward policy proposals.
</P>
<P>
Such a meeting began to convene from last year and was named "
Economic Summit."
</P>
<P>
Turkey is carrying on a three-year economic stability program
under a 4-billion-U.S.-dollar stand-by deal signed with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) last December.
</P>
<P>
Under the loan package approved by the IMF, Turkey pledged to
reduce its chronic inflation and budget deficits, undertake a
comprehensive privatization program and reform agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The government aims to reduce inflation to 20 percent in 2000,
10 percent in 2001 and 5.0 percent in 2002. The annual inflation
rate stood at 68.9 percent in January of this year.
</P>
<P>
Onal said that basic economic indicators like prices, interest
rates and foreign currency reserves should not be deviated a lot
from the world markets, making Turkey competitive against its rival
countries which provide the same goods and services for the global
market.
</P>
<P>
Labor and Social Security Minister Yasar Okuyan said that the
Social Security Reform, which plays an important role in Turkey's
anti-inflation campaign, has produced results.
</P>
<P>
The program did not receive financing support from the Treasury
in June, July and August of this year for the first time in the
last eight years, he said.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the new social security system in Turkey will
take shape in the next five years, and until 2050, the deficits of
all social security organizations were expected to be overcome
totally.
</P>
<P>
Fuat Miras, chairman of the Union of Turkish Chambers and
Commodity Exchanges, said that they would continue to extend every
support to the government in its struggle against inflation.
</P>
<P>
Miras said that the sacrifices that the whole country was
bearing, should gain later, adding that the economic circles should
send the message that they are supporting the government's
stability program to drop the runaway inflation.
</P>
<P>
He said that the stability program made major progress in the
first eight months of this year. "Structural reforms and necessary
economic legalization are very important developments," he said.
</P>
<P>
He hailed the financial policy within the framework of the
stability program as "very successful."
</P>
<P>
"There was an important decrease in the general budget deficit.
However, the public expenditure reform has yet to be adopted," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury head Selcuk Demiralp said that the government has
taken several measures, aiming at increasing public revenues and
cutting public expenses.
</P>
<P>
He said that the desired targets can easily be achieved within
three years if the economic stability program, including financial
discipline and structural reforms, is implemented without
concession.
</P>
<P>
He said that the economic performance in the first eight months
was "positive," adding that financial discipline will change macro-
economic imbalances blamed for the high chronic inflation and the
failure in a strong economic growth in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
So, the final target of the economic stability program is to
drop the inflation to one-digit number within three years, he said.
</P>
<P>
Although the government has targeted an economic growth rate of
5.5 percent this year, he believed that it would stand at 6-7
percent at the year end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
