<HEADLINE> Palestinian Leadership Announces to Delay Statehood Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Palestine Central Council (PCC)
decided Sunday to postpone the statehood declaration, Chairman of
the Palestine National Council Salem Zanoun announced.
</P>
<P>
Zanoun told reporters after the two-day meeting of the 129-
member PCC, the Palestinian policy making body, that the PCC will
meet again before November 15 to decide when to declare an
independent state.
</P>
<P>
From now on the Executive Committee of Palestine Liberation
Organization will be authorized to tackle all the statehood-related
issues, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said that several committees have been set up to prepare
legal papers for the establishment of an independent state.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leadership made the statehood postponement
decision so as to give peace another chance. Arafat said earlier in
the day the peace talks with Israel, which have been stalled since
the Camp David summit in July, will resume on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Leader Yasser Arafat had earlier said to declare an
independent state as early as on September 13, the deadline set
with Israel to reach a permanent peace deal to end the 52-year
conflict.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000910.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Leadership Announces to Delay Statehood Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Palestine Central Council (PCC)
decided Sunday to postpone the statehood declaration, Chairman of
the Palestine National Council Salem Zanoun announced.
</P>
<P>
Zanoun told reporters after the two-day meeting of the 129-
member PCC, the Palestinian policy making body, that the PCC will
meet again before November 15 to decide when to declare an
independent state.
</P>
<P>
From now on, the Executive Committee of Palestine Liberation
Organization will be authorized to take the necessary steps to
implement an independent state, he added.
</P>
<P>
Zanoun said the Palestinian leadership made the decision to give
peace another chance. Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said earlier
in the day the peace talks with Israel, which have been stalled
since the Camp David summit in July, will resume on Monday and
continue for five weeks.
</P>
<P>
Zanoun also said that several committees have been set up to
prepare legal papers for the establishment of an independent state,
which Arafat had earlier said to proclaim as early as on September
13, the deadline set with Israel for a permanent peace deal.
</P>
<P>
But the peace deal is as elusive as ever as the two sides remain
far apart over the key final-status issues, especially the future
of Jerusalem, which aborted the Camp David summit between Arafat,
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
At the Camp David summit, Barak offered the Palestinians limited
control over parts of the traditionally Arab East Jerusalem, but
the Palestinians held firm in their longstanding position that the
entire eastern section should be under Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied East Jerusalem in the 1967 Mideast war and later
annexed it in a move not recognized internationally. Palestinians
want the eastern part as capital of a future state, while Israel
insists it is part of its "undivided" capital.
</P>
<P>
After the collapse of the summit, Arafat had launched an
international tour to rally support for the declaration of a state,
but world leaders advised him not to take unilateral step to avoid
conceivable violence and give peace more chance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000910.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Minister Limits Visits to Jailed Former Shas Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Public Security
Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami Sunday decided to limit the number of
lawmakers who hope to visit the jailed former leader of the ultra-
Orthodox Shas party Aryeh Deri to one a week.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made on the recommendation of a special Prisons
Service committee on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Normally, Knesset (parliament) members are free to visit
prisoners as often as they wish but Deri, who began to serve his
three-year imprisonment term last week for fraud and bribe-taking,
has been deluged by visitors, including those from the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Deri supporters have set up a prayer tent outside the
Ma'asiyahu prison in Ramla near Tel Aviv, where Deri is
incarcerated.
</P>
<P>
The imprisonment of Deri, the charismatic former Shas leader and
the first cabinet minister ever given to prison terms in the
Israeli history, has sparked violent protests by his supporters.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the wave of protesting activities, Israeli chief
Rabbi Israel Lau said Sunday that he understood the feelings of the
Shas activists who sympathize with Deri, "as long as they don't
break the law, or beat a policeman or journalist, and as long as
they don't beat anyone."
</P>
<P>
Rabbi Lau met Sunday with President Moshe Katsav to discuss
the "secular revolution" initiated by Prime Minister Ehud Barak
last month to allow civil marriages, national service for all
including ultra-Orthodox yeshiva students and Arab youths, and the
abolition of the Ministry of Religious Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Rabbi Lau said that a country that values freedom of speech
cannot silence Shas supporters who express solidarity with "their
friend who is in prison," despite such solidarity "not having been
expressed for other people charged with similar offences."
</P>
<P>
Rabbi Lau also added that freedom of speech should not be
interpreted as freedom to incite or to slander.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the "secular revolution," Rabbi Lau said that he
does not think a secular or Ashkenazi revolution will take place in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Knesset should discuss the future of the
country and maintain the status quo regarding religious issues. "We
should look for things that build a bridge between us, not things
that increase the rift," he added.
</P>
<P>
Rabbi Lau praised Barak, saying that Barak had knowledge and
interest in Judaism that did not fall short of that of his
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
Barak's recent pledge to allow buses to run and the state-run
airline El Al to operate on Shabbat has caused a big stir in the
political spectrum, drawing outcry not only from the religious
parties but also from his own Labor party.
</P>
<P>
Shabbat is the Jewish holiday which bans secular activities such
as driving, flying and merchandising.
</P>
<P>
Despite Barak's explanation that bus services will be provided
specifically to take the carless poor residents in some areas to
the beach on Shabbat, the move is seen by many as Barak's efforts
to woo the secular vote in the preparation for a possible early
election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
