<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Pharmaceutical Companies Urged to Manufacture HIV/Aids Drugs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He told the Zimbabwe News Agency that such a move would
drastically reduce the price of the much-needed drugs, making them
more affordable to the poor who are the worst affected in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister joined other African health ministers in
expressing concern over the exorbitant prices of anti-retroviral
drugs sold by international pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Theoretically, even if these drugs cost 10 U.S.
dollars a month per person, the majority of our people would still
not be able to afford them. That is why poverty and health are
inter-twined."
</P>
<P>
He was recently in Ouagadougou where he attended the 50th
session of the World Health Organization (WHO) regional meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe was opposed to getting loans for HIV drugs as
this would worsen the debt crisis in most African countries.
</P>
<P>
He proposed that the international pharmaceutical companies
consider financing HIV and Aids programs, especially the provision
of anti-retroviral drugs for the worst affected countries like
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister said the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) planned to procure anti-retroviral drugs for the
region. This was cost-effective and would bring closer regional
unity. 
</P>
