<HEADLINE> SADC to Launch Common Electricity Supply Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
They said at a meeting of the members of the Southern African
Power Pool (SAPP) preparation committee that once set up in one of
the SADC cities, the market will rally efforts and resources of
SADC members to jointly solve their power problems.
</P>
<P>
They said that the project would involve interconnecting the
national grids of the SADC member states to enable utilization of
excessive power within the region.
</P>
<P>
"The essence of creating such a market is to optimize the
electricity load profile of the member states in dealing with
problems like unpredicted power cuts which are a common phenomenon
in various SADC countries," they added.
</P>
<P>
A report for the project has been prepared by three power
companies, the TANESCO of Tanzania, the ESKOM of South Africa and
the ZESCO of Zambia, recommending construction of a 670-kilometer,
330-kilovolt transmission line from Pensulo, Zambia to Mbeya,
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Arrangements are underway to get a private firm to undertake
the project, they said, without giving further details.
</P>
<P>
"Similarly, Kenya, which is currently facing acute power
shortage, could have brought power from any of the southern
African countries if Kenya's national gird is interconnected with
that of Tanzania and the Tanzanian one connected with that of
Zambia which is already connected with most of the states in the
south," they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
