<DOCNO> XIE20000910.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blockades Partially Paralyze Traffic in Brussels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- When some 1,700 trucks
honked and blared on Sunday, they were not celebrating the
Brussels Liberation Day that fell on the day.
</P>
<P>
They were loudly protesting against the ever-rising fuel prices
that have cut into the earnings of truck drivers.
</P>
<P>
The one-day protest was originally scheduled to end by mid-
afternoon and yet between 600 and 700 heavy-duty trucks refused to
leave downtown Brussels and they stopped side by side or
lengthwise on major streets to set up road blockades.
</P>
<P>
Holiday-makers as well as ordinary road users had to meander
their way through the city's smaller and back streets to get to
their destination.
</P>
<P>
Drivers of the leftover trucks said that they would not leave
until three o'clock on Monday morning, 12 hours after their
planned come-and-go drive-by protest has ended.
</P>
<P>
The protest, organized by the Union of Professional Road
Transport of Belgium, was aimed at persuading government
authorities to cut tax on fuels and levy more from the profits
made by oil refinery and distribution companies.
</P>
<P>
Most of the protesting trucks bore eminent catch-words of "SOS",
"same VAT for all" and "less social charges for more earnings".
</P>
<P>
One protesting truck driver told journalists that the rising
fuel prices are killing road transport and that can be interpreted
as indirectly killing the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
A European Union survey has found that more than 79 percent of
land transport is now carried by motor vehicles in the European
Union countries.
</P>
<P>
Also participating in the protest were coaches, tanker trucks,
taxis, school buses, engineering vehicles, family cars, inter-city
buses and even motorbikes.
</P>
<P>
Another truck driver said that he was out before seven to take
part in the day's protest that followed a week-long road blockade
by truck drivers in neighboring France and truck driver
demonstrations in Germany and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Fuel prices, both petrol and diesel, rose by close to 20
percent in the last three years in Belgium. A liter of petrol now
costs around 48 Belgian francs (1.06 U.S. dollars) while a liter
of diesel costs around 35 francs (77 cents).
</P>
<P>
The protesters were demanding that the authorities reduce
government taxes on fuels and increase taxation on the profits
made by oil refinery and distribution companies.
</P>
<P>
Protesters claimed that TotalFinaElf, for one, made 136 percent
more profit in the first seven months this year to total 137
billion francs (3 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, the finance ministers from all 15 European Union
member states on Saturday indicated a "no change" of government
taxation policy regarding tax reduction for petroleum products in
the EU countries.
</P>
<P>
The EU ministers, however, urged the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries to increase production so as to reduce oil
prices during their weekend meeting in Vienna. They hoped that oil
prices could return to a level that preserves worldwide growth.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Budget Minister Johan Vande Lanotte estimated that the
rising prices of crude oil alone cost his country 15 billion
Belgian francs (33.3 million U.S. dollars) more this year and that
could mean a decrease of revenue next year in the amount of 25
billion francs (55.5 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The rocketing of oil prices posted since early 1999 has
triggered a debate in the EU on crude oil prices, refining and
distribution as well as taxation on oil products, the three
components of fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
The EU officials would hold the tight production quota by the
OPEC responsible for the rising crude oil prices that in turn had
led to rising fuel prices elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil prices now seem determined to fluctuate within a band
of 30 U.S. dollars a barrel and it entered that band in February
this year following an uninterrupted rise since December 1998 when
the crude oil price bottomed out at 10 dollars a barrel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000910.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Canada Revealed as Safest Carrier by European Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Air Canada, the national
carrier, has been revealed as the world's safest airline by a
European development bank, the Ottawa Citizen newspaper said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A passenger on one of its flights has only one-in-1.3 million
chance of being involved in any kind of accident, as is shown in a
table of risk commissioned by the bank in a bid to avoid booking
its staff with dangerous carriers.
</P>
<P>
The new table combines the accident history of airlines with 10
other safety factors, including management structure, fleet
composition and safety regulation in its home country. Under
traditional criteria, airlines have been assessed only by the
number of accidents.
</P>
<P>
"The law has changed over the years so that employers are more
responsible for their employees. Companies are increasingly keen
to minimize their exposure to risk," said John Trevett, who will
give details of his ranking system at the Aircraft Quality and
Safety Conference in Brussels this week.
</P>
<P>
Trevett, a former test pilot and a senior lecturer at Cranfield
University in Britain, spent three years developing the table,
which has been adopted by the International Association of Oil and
Gas Producers in collaboration with Shell and the European Bank
for Reconstruction and Development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
