<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Kick Off Parliamentary Elections on October 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will hold the next
parliamentary elections in three stages as of October 18,
Information Minister Safwat el-Sharif said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken during a ministerial meeting in the
Mediterranean port city of Alexandria chaired by President Hosni
Mubarak, el-Sharif was quoted as saying by the country's Middle
East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is expected to issue a republican decree next Sunday,
envisaging the elections of the next People's Assembly will be held
in three phases between October 18 and November 15, the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
El-Sharif said the first stage will run from October 18 to 25,
the second from October 29 to November 5 and the third from
November 8 to 15.
</P>
<P>
It is for the first time in Egypt's 134-year parliamentary
history that the parliamentary elections will be supervised by the
judiciary and carried out in three stages, rather than on a single
day.
</P>
<P>
According to an election plan worked out by the Interior
Ministry, there will be a total of 10,718 polling stations in 222
constituencies across the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
Under Egyptian laws, the parliament has 454 members, of which
444 are elected by voters and the other 10 are appointed by the
president.
</P>
<P>
The republican decree stipulates that the new People's Assembly
opens session on December 14, el-Sharif said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
