<DOCNO> XIE20000910.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> West Nile Virus Spreads to Horses in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Blood tests conducted by
Israel's Veterinary Services have confirmed that at least 15 horses
in the central part of the country are suffering from the West Nile
fever, the Environment Ministry said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The animals were tested during the last two days after they
showed signs of weakness and instability, but the West Nile virus
does not make them wild, the ministry added.
</P>
<P>
The virus is transmitted by mosquitoes and the fields outside
the stables are being sprayed with anti-mosquito insecticide, the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry added that it has received more than 3,000
complaints of mosquito infections in the past few days and local
councils are having difficulties in meeting the demand for
neighborhood spraying.
</P>
<P>
Some 30 Israelis have been infected so far by the virus and
three elderly patients in their 80s have died of illnesses caused
by the virus.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry on Friday held a meeting with health
experts, some of whom criticized the ministry for not doing enough
to increase public awareness of the virus, which often causes a
rash and slight fever in its victims but can be fatal to certain
vulnerable populations, particularly the elderly.
</P>
<P>
The virus, found in birds, is spread by mosquitoes which bite
the birds and then pass the virus on when biting humans, the
experts said.
</P>
<P>
Health Ministry officials said it is not clear whether there is
an outbreak of the virus, which has been known to exist in Israel
for at least 50 years.
</P>
<P>
There is no preventive medication against the virus in Israel
and the only available means of protection is pest control.
</P>
</TEXT>
