<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Talks to Free Remaining Iranian, Iraq POWs Under Way: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Iraq have started
talks with the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) for
the exchange of the remaining prisoners of war (POWs) still held in
each other's country, a senior Iranian official said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
All evidence related to Iranian POWs and those missing in the
1980-1988 Iran-Iraq war have been submitted to the ICRC, and the
exchange of the remaining POWs will start after an agreement is
reached with Baghdad, said Brigadier General Abdollah Najafi, head
of Iran's commission for POWs.
</P>
<P>
Quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency, the official said
that some 97 percent of Iraqi and Iranian POWs have so far been
repatriated through the offices of the ICRC.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of the war between the two neighbors, Iran has
released 59,830 Iraqi POWs while Iraq has repatriated 39,417
Iranian POWs, he said, adding that the remaining 3 percent of POWs
are to be exchanged when an agreement is reached.
</P>
<P>
Iran unilaterally released 728 Iraqi POWs last month, bringing
to 4,117 the total number of Iraq POWs released since the start of
the current Iranian year on March 20.
</P>
<P>
After the release, Najafi claimed that Iran had freed all
remaining Iraqi POWs. But he said that more than 7,000 Iraqis were
unwilling to return to Iraq and chose to stay in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Despite the claim, Baghdad holds that Iran still keep captive
29,000 Iraqi POWs, and Iran also accuses Iraq of holding over 3,000
Iranians.
</P>
<P>
Unless the issue is solved completely, it will remain a major
stumbling block for normalization of ties between the two
neighbors, whose 1980-1988 war cost nearly 1 million lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
