<HEADLINE> Geological Experts on Potential for Oil Exploration on Lake Malawi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Malawian geological experts
said vital information is missing to fully establish the existence
of oil on the bed of Lake Malawi, the third largest lake in Africa,
a report reaching here said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Charles Kamphiyo, director of Malawi's geological survey, told
journalists various research and oil exploration companies have
since 1981 only confirmed the existence of sedimentary rocks which
could be hydrocarbon (oil and gas) bearing.
</P>
<P>
"The only way to determine if there are hydrocarbons under Lake
Malawi bed is to sink an exploratory drill hole to penetrate the
strata," he said in an interview on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Lake Malawi, covering about 25,000 square kilometers, occupies
one third of the entire Malawi. Part of it stretches into its
northern neighbors of Tanzania and Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The freshwater lake lies at the southern end of the African
rift valley, which is 560 kilometers long, 80 kilometers wide, 722
meters at its deepest point and lies about 474 meters above sea
level.
</P>
<P>
Kamphiyo said surveys had indicated thick sediments of
hydrocarbons which have the potential of hosting oil.
</P>
<P>
"All we are trying to do is to sell the idea to the
international world that we have potential for oil exploration,"
he said, adding: "There is a lot of exploration work to be done,
more especially to drill a few holes to enable us to know what is
down there."
</P>
<P>
Noting that oil exploration "is an expensive and high risk
venture that requires specialized technology and substantial risk
capital," Kamphiyo said since 1989, no other international oil
company had ventured into hydrocarbons exploration of Lake Malawi.
</P>
<P>
The first research on oil and gas on Lake Malawi was conducted
in 1981 by Duke University of America. The survey revealed that
thick sequences of up to three kilometers of sedimentary rocks
were present under wide areas of the lakebed, raising the status
of the lake as a target for hydrocarbon exploration.
</P>
<P>
Kamphiyo mentioned international efforts for oil exploration on
the lake by Shell Exploration B.V. of the Netherlands, Hunt's
International and Mobil Oil corporation, but all failed.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he said: "We will keep on promoting the lake for
oil exploration."
</P>
<P>
Malawi imports all its petroleum products from abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
