<HEADLINE> Postponing Statehood Declaration Most Likely: Senior Palestinian Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The dominant opinion in the
ongoing session of the Palestinian Central Council (PCC) was for
postponing statehood declaration to late this year, Palestinian
National Council (PNC) Chairman Salim Zanoun said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Before attending the PCC morning session, Zanoun said, "All
speech makers unanimously agreed that the statehood declaration
delay should not exceed the end of this year."
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "Few members proposed an open postponement"
and explained that "an open delay provides (Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud) Barak with the opportunity to go ahead with his plans to get
us remain under endless limited self-rule."
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Zanoun threatened to quit his post as head of the
Palestinian legislative body, in case the Palestinian statehood
declaration was postponed to a post-2000 date.
</P>
<P>
Some PNC members proposed that Palestine Liberation Organization
(PLO)'s Executive Committee should follow up the developments until
another date was set for declaring the independent Palestinian
state or invite the PCC, the PLO's mini lawmaking body, for another
meeting to take the proper decision.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the potential dates, Zanoun said, "PCC meeting on
February 2, l999 set the end of this year for the planned
declaration."
</P>
<P>
The end of this year, Zanoun said, means either November 15, the
anniversary of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's 1988 symbolic
declaration of independence in Algiers, or January 1, the date
marking the beginning of the armed struggle against Israel by
Arafat's group, Fatah
</P>
<P>
He denied as "baseless" the report quoted by local Al-Quds daily
from Agence France Press (AFP) that Arafat was angry with Zanoun
over the reshuffle in the PCC, stressing that "restructuring the
PCC should take place after the Palestinian statehood declaration,
not before it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
