<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Not to Retract Shabath Transport Statements: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak will not retract his statements regarding the establishment
of public transportations on the Shabath and permitting Israel's
national carrier El Al to operate on weekends, Israel Radio
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Shabath, which starts Friday evening and ends Saturday evening,
is the weekend holiday for the Jews. During the Shabath, El Al has
to ground all its planes while public transportations have to stop
their operations and Jewish people have to stay at home reading
bibles. Despite wide-ranging criticism, Barak will not retract
his statements, but will try to continue this "civil revolution"
and initiate such changes, the report quoted sources close to Barak
as saying.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel's Television Channel 1 from New York
on Friday, Barak said his government should take the advantage of
the fact that there are no religious parties in the coalition to
initiate the "civil revolution" by implementing the plans to run
buses in Tel Aviv and have El Al planes to fly on Shabath.
</P>
<P>
Criticism was hurled at Barak both from the religious parties
and his own One Israel party following the weekend statements.
</P>
<P>
The ultra-Orthodox Shas party Chairman Eli Yishai said on Sunday
that the prime minister's acts were "hysterical," while National
Religious Party (NRP) Chairman Yitzhak Levy said Barak "is making a
mistake."
</P>
<P>
Senior party members of One Israel also said on Sunday that
Barak's intentions oppose party policy to maintain the status quo
in relations between religion and state.
</P>
<P>
"All the internal surveys say that 70 percent of members and
supporters of the party want to continue with the status quo. If
Barak wants to change this, he has to bring the topic to debate
within the party where he would meet strong opposition," a party
source told the radio.
</P>
<P>
Responding to Barak's plans, Minister Without Portfolio Michael
Melchior from Meimad party said Friday that his party would not
agree to an initiative to separate religion and state and "totally
abolish Shabath in Israel."
</P>
<P>
"The cooperation between Meimad and One Israel is based on a
recognition of Israel as a Jewish state and democratic state,
whereby its Jewish character is strengthened. I am convinced that
the prime minister does not intend to break the rules," he said,
adding that "Meimad would bot be a partner to such a thing."
</P>
<P>
Meimad holds one of the 26 Knesset (parliament) seats in the
Labor Party-led One Israel alliance. The third partner, former
foreign minister David Levy's Gesher (Bridge) party, quit the
alliance early August over Barak's peace policies.
</P>
<P>
Barak has been implementing a "civil reform" plan that has
already included a cabinet vote on disbanding the Ministry of
Religious Affairs. He hopes to work on drafting a constitution and
allowing anyone to be married in a civil ceremony instead of a
religious one.
</P>
<P>
Last week, acting Transportation Minister Amnon Lipkin-Shahak
said that El Al might begin to fly on Shabath before the
privatization move is completed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
