<HEADLINE> Iran Seizes 1.5 Tons of Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran's security forces on
Sunday seized some 1,500 kilograms of opium in the Mir-Javeh border
region in the southeastern Sistan-Baluchestan province, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The province borders war-torn Afghanistan, the world's largest
opium producer.
</P>
<P>
Brigadier General Naser Shabani, commander of the provincial
security forces, told the agency that eight camels and some weapons
were also confiscated from the international smugglers during the
operation. However, the smugglers have fled across the border.
</P>
<P>
Drug hauls have become common in Iran as it sits on a major
route for smuggling narcotics from the eastern neighbors of
Afghanistan and Pakistan to the lucrative markets in the Persian
Gulf, Europe and Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
In July, Iran closed down 725 kilometers of its borders with
Afghanistan as part of the stepped-up efforts to combat drug trade.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Majlis (parliament) has earmarked 200 billion rials
(about 24.4 million U.S. dollars) in credits to block the eastern
borders from drug traffic.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, 740 drug traffickers and 174 Iranian police officers
were killed in narcotics-related confrontations, according to
government reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
