<HEADLINE> Israeli Official Blames Jewish Settlers for Hebron Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Deputy Defense
Minister Ephraim Sneh on Sunday criticized the Jewish settlers in
the West Bank city of Hebron for causing the violent climate there.
</P>
<P>
Sneh, who was touring the city, charged that some members in the
Jewish community in Hebron are more responsible than the
Palestinians for the rise in violence in the volatile city, said
Israeli Radio reports.
</P>
<P>
The minister said some people from both sides in the city are
trying to riot up the situation. But "much to my regret," said
Sneh, "our information points to the Jewish settlers as being
responsible for the violent incidents recently."
</P>
<P>
Members of the Jewish community in Hebron refused to meet with
Sneh, accusing him of constantly defaming them at every
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, Hebron, the only city divided between areas of
Israeli and Palestinian control, has been the scene of a wave of
violent incidents between Jewish settlers and Arabs. The Israel
Defense Forces spoke of an atmosphere of growing extremism which,
to a large extent, has been created by settlers in the Jewish
enclave.
</P>
<P>
Hebron is now home to 130,000 Palestinians and 450 Jewish
settlers living in 63 settlements.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian media last month quoted Palestinian chief
negotiator Saeb Erekat as saying that Israel had agreed to evacuate
the Jews from Hebron, which evoked strong denial from Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and angry response from the settlers.
</P>
<P>
In response, Jewish settlers in Hebron vowed to start a "
struggle without limits" on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The future of settlements on the West Bank and Gaza Strip is one
of the tough issues to be settled by the Israelis and Palestinians
in the final-status negotiations, which also include the status of
Jerusalem, border, water resources, and the return of Palestinian
refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
