<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- A gas pipeline will be built from Iran to Armenia to
help promote gas trade between the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the 141-kilometer pipeline is to be completed
in the fall of 2001. Once the whole line is completed, it could
carry 1.5 million cubic meters of gas per day to Armenia.
</P>
<P>
A consortium comprising Russian company Gazprom, French company
Gaz de France, the National Iranian Gas Company and the Armenian
Energy Ministry will be set up for the project, which costs some
124 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Britain has decided to help rebuild a quake-hit
Turkish province.
</P>
<P>
Under a memorandum of understanding signed between the British
and Turkish governments Saturday, Britain undertakes to carry out a
master plan designed by British companies to rebuild Yalova,
northwestern province that is among the hardest hit by the August
1999 earthquake.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 850 million dollars in financing is needed for the
rehabilitation work, which will primarily be performed by British
companies active in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Haitian Minister of Commerce and Industry Gerald
Germain invited investments from Turkey, saying that his Caribbean
Island state is a good place for Turkish textile industry
investors.
</P>
<P>
Germain made the call when he was visiting Ekrem Demirtas,
chairman of the Chamber of Commerce in Izmir, southwest Turkey,
during the just-concluded Izmir International Fair.
</P>
<P>
Demirtas agreed, referring to the fact that the United States
does not apply textile sector quotas to Haiti.
</P>
<P>
"Haiti enjoys a privileged position vis-a-vis U.S. quotas and
could be a strategic textile and ready-made garment base for
Turkish merchants," he said.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- World Bank has agreed to extend a 21.3-million-dollar
soft loan for supporting Yemen's torrential irrigation system.
</P>
<P>
Yemen's Industry Ministry said the credit would be used to carry
out strategic programs designated to improve and rehabilitate the
irrigation system of a 213-acre area.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the European Union (EU) has agreed on extending a 6-
million-dollar financial grant for Yemeni water, sewerage and
infrastructure projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
