<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Ruling Party Candidate Killed Amid Elections Campaigning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A ruling party candidate for
Sri Lanka's October general elections was shot dead Sunday by
unidentified gunmen in the eastern district of Batticaloa as
elections campaigning was in full swing, police sources said.
</P>
<P>
Cheliyan Perinpanayagam of the People's Alliance (PA) was
gunned down in a village near Batticaloa town, some 300 kilometers
east of Colombo, said the sources, adding that one of his key
supporters was also killed.
</P>
<P>
Commandos of the elite Special Task Force rushed to the scene
on receipt of the information and searched the area for the gunmen
who had got away by then, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Perinpanayagam, a former mayor of Batticaloa town, recently
joined the PA after resigning from a Tamil party. He is the first
candidate to be killed in the run-up to the October 10 general
elections. No one has yet claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Security was tightened throughout the country last week as
campaigning for the elections began amidst fears of poll-related
violence and assassination attempts by Tamil Tiger rebels.
</P>
<P>
At least five people have been killed in election-related
violence since the 10th parliament was dissolved on August 18.
</P>
