<HEADLINE> Nigeria Rejects Accusations Over S. Leonean Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian military has
rejected as outrageous claims allegedly accusing its senior
officers of deliberately undermining the Indian United Nations
commander in Sierra Leone by maintaining close contacts with local
rebel groups and being more interested in pursuing business deals,
said a source reaching here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Nigeria has done more than any country, laid down more lives
than any other country, to fight the rebels in Sierra Leone," an
anonymous senior military officer was quoted as saying on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The officer said that claims in a leaked confidential U.N.
report, purportedly written by Indian U.N. commander in Sierra
Leone Major General Vijay Jetley, allegedly accusing Nigerian
officials of maintaining close contacts with the rebel
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) in return for diamonds were "
outrageous".
</P>
<P>
In the four-page report, Jetley allegedly charged Nigerians of
plotting a conspiracy to force him out as the U.N. commander in
the west African country, saying that he had become a victim of
the machinations of these countries which were trying to scuttle
the peace process in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
However, Nigerian military officials said that Jetley's claims
do not fully reflect Nigeria's role in the civil war in the west
African country.
</P>
<P>
A senior Nigerian military official noted that his country in
1998 sent thousands of troops into Sierra Leone to oust a RUF-
allied rebel government and restored to power the elected
president Ahmad Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
It was also Nigerian forces to expel the RUF from the capital
Freetown in January 1999 when the RUF attacked the capital city,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Differences between Nigerian and Indian forces in Sierra Leone
have long been "an open secret". Nigeria had publicly campaigned
for the removal of Jetley, declaring that he should be replaced by
a Nigerian because Nigeria supplies the largest troop contingent
in Sierra Leone. 
</P>
