<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgians Protest Against Rising Fuel Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- It was quite a spectacle
when more than 2,000 motor vehicles, mostly heavy-duty trucks and
tourist coaches, honked and blared on Sunday in downtown Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Instead of celebrating the Brussels Liberation Day that fell on
Sunday, they were protesting against the ever-rising fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
The high noon driving-by protesters, organized by the Union of
Professional Road Transport of Belgium, meandered its way by the
European Union (EU) institutions and the high streets of Brussels,
causing traffic difficulties for Sunday holiday-makers.
</P>
<P>
One police officer said that it was the first time for him to
see so many motor vehicles moving in to protest.
</P>
<P>
Most of the protesting vehicles bore eminent catch-words of "
SOS", "same VAT for all" and "less social charges for more
earnings."
</P>
<P>
A truck driver taking part in the demonstration said the rising
fuel prices are killing not only road transport business, but also
the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
An EU survey shows that trucks transport more than 79 percent
of the land-shipping goods in the EU member countries.
</P>
<P>
Also participating in the one-day protest included tanker
trucks, taxis, school buses, engineering vehicles, family cars,
commuter buses and motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
The one-day protest, said a truck driver, is to support the
week-long road blockades in neighboring France and truck driver
demonstrations in Germany and Britain.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that petrol and diesel prices have increased by
about 20 percent in the last three years in Belgium. A liter of
petrol now costs around 48 Belgian francs (1.06 U.S. dollars), and
a liter of diesel, 35 francs (77 cents).
</P>
<P>
The protesters were demanding the authorities reduce taxes on
fuels and increase taxes on the profits earned by oil refinery and
distribution companies.
</P>
<P>
Protesters claimed that Total Fina Elf, for example, made 136
percent more profit in the first seven months of this year to
reach 137 billion francs (3 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, the finance ministers from all the 15 EU member states
expressed a "no change" of government taxation policy regarding
reduction of taxes on petroleum products in EU countries during
their Saturday meeting in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
Instead, they urged the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) to increase oil production so as to reduce oil
prices at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
They also hoped that oil prices could return to a level that
preserves worldwide growth.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Budget Minister Johan Vande Lanotte estimated that the
rising prices of crude oil alone cost his country 15 billion
Belgian francs (33.3 million U.S. dollars) more this year and that
could mean a decrease of revenue of 25 billion francs (55.5
million dollars) next year.
</P>
<P>
The rocketing oil prices since early 1999 has triggered a
debate in the EU on the crude oil prices, oil refining and
distribution as well as taxation on oil products.
</P>
<P>
The EU officials would hold the tight production quota by the
OPEC responsible for the rising crude oil prices that in turn have
led to rising fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil prices now seem determined to fluctuate within a band
of 30 dollars a barrel and it entered that band in February this
year following an uninterrupted rise since December 1998 when the
crude oil price bottomed out at 10 dollars a barrel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
