<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Legislative Council Elections Begin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region's second Legislative Council elections began
at 7:30 am Sunday, with over 3.05 million registered voters
expected to cast their ballots.
</P>
<P>
A total of 526 polling stations throughout Hong Kong are open to
voters until 10:30 pm Sunday. Six counting stations have been set
up.
</P>
<P>
There are 155 valid nominees competing for 60 LegCo seats, with
88 candidates for 24 geographical constituency seats, 48
candidates for 21 functional constituency seats, and 10 candidates
contesting six seats via the Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
Voters of the Geographical Constituencies are required to mark
a tick in the circle next to the list of candidates he/she has
chosen with a chop provided by polling staff.
</P>
<P>
In the Functional Constituencies elections, nine candidates had
been elected uncontested.
</P>
<P>
Except the Transport Functional Constituency, voters of the
remaining 18 Functional Constituencies should mark the ballot
papers with a chop provided by polling staff.
</P>
<P>
For the Election Committee election, each voter is required to
choose six candidates by shading in black the ovals against the
names of the six candidates of his/her choice with a pen provided
by polling staff.
</P>
<P>
To make the elections transparent and fair, the results will be
broadcast at one-hour intervals via a government website or the
media.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Electoral Affairs Commission Woo Kwok-hing and
two commission members will inspect 19 different polling stations
in different parts of Hong Kong to monitor polling activities.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
