<HEADLINE> Racket Involving Policemen in Zambia's Capital Uncovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A racket involving two
policemen in Zambia's capital Lusaka has been uncovered, according
to Sunday Times of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The two policemen are being investigated for maliciously
impounding vehicles in order to duplicate keys for passing on to
car thieves.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted police spokesman Lemmy Kajoba as calling on
residents who may have experienced similar incidents to report to
police to ask for a help.
</P>
<P>
At least three Lusaka victims have lost their vehicles which
were impounded by the same policemen a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
Kajoba said police will soon start carrying out random checks
at locksmiths shops in the city to ensure that they are legitimate
and that they operate within the law.
</P>
<P>
He said the mushrooming of locksmith companies is a
contributing factor to the rise in car thefts.
</P>
<P>
There are over 20 locksmith companies in Lusaka. 
</P>
