<HEADLINE> S. Korea, DPR Korea Will March Together in Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 10 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and DPR Korea will
march together for the first time at an Olympics when the
Millennium Olympics open here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
International Olympic Committee (IOC) president Juan Antonio
Samaranch announced the decision late Sunday at the opening of an
IOC session.
</P>
<P>
"The IOC is very pleased to annunce an agreement has been
reached between the National Olympic Committees of South Korea and
the Demoractic People's Republic of Korea," Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to thank the two National Olympic Committees. I
think this is very good news for sport," he told the IOC members.
</P>
<P>
After negotiations between Olympic officials and the Koreas,
Samaranch said earlier in the day that he was optimistic about an
agreement, saying that "we are negotiating. We have the last
meeting maybe this afternoon. I would like to have the answer for
the opening ceremony."
</P>
<P>
A senior IOC disclosed that the Koreans will be marching
together but not behind the Olympic flag. Instead they will have
their own flag.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time the Koreas have walked together at an
Olympic opening ceremony which is broadcast live throughout the
world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
