<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Finance Ministers Meeting Ends in Brunei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bandar Seri Begawan, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The 7th meeting
of finance ministers of the 21 APEC member economies concluded
here Sunday with a statement for member economies to adopt
effective policies for ensuring sustainable growth in the region.
</P>
<P>
The ministers discussed the regional economy and measures to
ensure the sustainable growth necessary for increased economy
prosperity in the region, a joint statement issued at the end of
their two-day meeting said.
</P>
<P>
"We resolve to continue to pursue sound economic and financial
policies and to carry out the structural reforms necessary to
sustain this progress," the ministers said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
On economic and financial situation, the ministers expressed
satisfaction with the efforts of each economy in overcoming the
negative impact of the Asia financial crisis, regaining the
momentum of economic growth and maintaining high level of growth
rate.
</P>
<P>
"However, there is no room for complacency...Much remains to be
done to implement crucial financial and corporate sector
restructuring and to strengthen key domestic financial, economic
and judicial institutions," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers reached a consensus that sustainable growth is
the prerequisite for regional stability and prosperity and to this
end, they urged each economy to adopt effective macro-economic
policies and conduct in-depth reform and economic restructuring so
as to ensure steady and sustainable development of regional
economy.
</P>
<P>
On global financial system, the ministers stated that it is
important to get the views of all economies in discussions on
global financial issues and sought broader representation in this
debate.
</P>
<P>
They noted that progress has been made in developing
international standards, codes and best practice guidelines in a
wide range of areas and supported the key standards identified by
the Financial Stability Forum and encouraged APEC economies to
implement them in accordance with their circumstances and
priorities.
</P>
<P>
In the light of the growing importance of cross-border capital
mobility, the ministers emphasized the significance of
strengthening the collection, dissemination and sharing of data on
cross-border capital flows to cover both debt and non-debt flows.
</P>
<P>
They also emphasized the importance of constructive engagement
to assist economies to strengthen regulatory and supervisory
frameworks.
</P>
<P>
The ministers supported the efforts of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) and its members to engage in a comprehensive
review of its core facilities to ensure more effective use of its
resources.
</P>
<P>
They endorsed the policy conclusions of the Voluntary Action
Plan for Promoting Freer and More Stable Capital Flows, saying "We
therefore resolve to continue policy reforms that enable us to
take advantage of the opportunities available in international
capital markets. We will establish in APEC a voluntary policy
dialogue on strengthening financial markets, particularly focusing
on issues related to the implementation of international financial
standards and codes."
</P>
<P>
On strengthening economic and corporate governance, the
ministers said sound economic and corporate governance will
encourage the return of capital to the region. "APEC will
undertake a policy dialogue on strengthening corporate governance
in this region, starting in early 2001."
</P>
<P>
The ministers have formed a task force on company accounting
and financial reporting to improve the quality of financial
disclosure and auditing practices in APEC economies.
</P>
<P>
On fighting financial crimes, the ministers welcomed the
agreement to establish an APEC working group that would conduct a
survey of the domestic, legal and regulatory frameworks for
fighting financial crime and recognized the need for strong
measures to combat money laundering, tax evasion, financial fraud
and other criminal or unethical activities.
</P>
<P>
Recognizing that information technology has the potential to
increase sustainable economic growth, the ministers called on
economies to formulate and implement appropriate policies and
arrangements to facilitate electronic transactions.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that a working group on electronic payment systems,
consisting of financial experts from member economies, would be
established to develop and implement programs to foster paperless
trading.
</P>
<P>
Besides the APEC finance ministers, senior representatives from
IMF, the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank also attended
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The 8th APEC Finance Ministers Meeting will be held in Suzhou,
China in September 2001 and as the incoming host, China made a
multi-media presentation to all the participants of its
preparatory programs under way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
