<HEADLINE> Kenyan Legislators' High Salary Increments Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's local government
officials have spoken against Members of Parliament for awarding
themselves high salary increments.
</P>
<P>
"Members of Parliament are our enemy number one," the East
African Standard quoted the councilors as saying in a statement
issued Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a seminar organized by the Association of Local Government
Authorities of Kenya, the councilors across the country complained
that local officials should not be left out in terms of the salary
raise.
</P>
<P>
They demanded that all district officials should receive a 100
percent increase in salaries.
</P>
<P>
However, the local officials did not cite the poverty situation
in the country as the reason to criticize the legislators, but
mentioned their relatively low salary.
</P>
<P>
Nairobi Deputy Mayor Joe Aketch noted that while the
legislators were earning 650,000 shillings (about 8,600 U.S.
dollars) including allowances per month, monthly salaries for
local officials were only 10,000 shillings (about 130 dollars) or
below.
</P>
<P>
Over half of Kenyans are still living under the poverty line
with less one dollar per day.
</P>
<P>
On August 1, the National Assembly of Kenya passed a bill to
raise increase transport allowance from around 1,000 dollars to
about 3,500 dollars, which has led to massive public opposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
