<HEADLINE> IOC President Gets Apology from Olympics Minister for Bus No-show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SYDNEY, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Australian Olympics Minister
Michael Knight gave his personal apology to Juan Antonio Samaranch
after the International Olympic Committee president was left
stranded when his bus failed to turn up.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch and the rest of the IOC executive board had planned
to visit the Olympic broadcast center on Saturday but cancelled
because the bus laid on by Games organizers was delayed for more
than 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"We waited 25 minutes outside the hotel and were told that it
could be another 10 so the president called off the trip, " one
executive board member said.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch confirmed Sunday he had been forced to cancel but
denied he had been furious.
</P>
<P>
"Not true. I was not angry," he said during a tour of the
athletes village.
</P>
<P>
"It was very easy to explain. We cancelled the trip because
the bus was not there. We were waiting for 20-25 minutes. They
said it would be 10 minutes more. It was not possible (to continue
with the planned visit). I had a very important meeting."
</P>
<P>
Samaranch said Knight, who has reportedly annoyed IOC
officials by what they see as a high handed attitude, had phoned
him from Melbourne to offer his personal apology.
</P>
<P>
And the transport official responsible for the mix-up had been
personally spoken to by the IOC president.
</P>
<P>
"I was very kind with him. Even I gave to him a small present,
" said Samaranch, adding that he understand there could be
transport problems from time to time.
</P>
<P>
"Every time in every Games there are difficulties with
transportation, in all Games ... in all Games ... this is not an
exception," he said. 
</P>
