<HEADLINE> "Three Musketeers" of Thai Tennis to Compete in Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Tennis "Three
Musketeers" of Paradorn Srichaphan, Tamarine Tanasugarn and
Benjamas Sangaram finally made it to the Sydney Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Tamarine, the most famous tennis player in the kingdom, walked
into the Olympiad on her 42nd world ranking, while Paradorn and
Benjamas win their Olympic berths as wild carders of the
International Tennis Federation.
</P>
<P>
The Millennium Olympics marks not only the largest number of
Thai tennis players ever to compete in the Olympiad, but also the
first time that the Kingdom will attend both the men's and women's
singles apart from the women's doubles.
</P>
<P>
In the 1992 and 1996 Olympics, Thailand only made their entries
in the women's doubles when Benjamas and another female player
lose in the first round in 1992, and Benjamas and Tamarine fought
their way into the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
The "Three Musketeers" are aiming to reap a better result when
they march onto the Sydney tennis courts as underdogs.
</P>
<P>
Considering the world-class opponents, their hopes of an
Olympic medal is bleak. However, the trio has the capability to
win tough matches and to top some of the big names, said Olarn
Issara, the Thai tennis team coach.
</P>
<P>
The 21-year-old Paradon, who ranks 85th in the world and is the
first Thai male tennis player to attend the Olympiad, has less
experiences when compared with top players, but he is confident of
upsetting those elite players.
</P>
<P>
"Although I am still young and my ranking is not quite high, I
think I can match any top guy if I can maintain my form," he said.
</P>
<P>
Among the trio, Tamarine should have the best run, provided she
is not drawn into a tough section, said Olarn. "On her day, the 23-
year-old female player can be a hard nut to crack and is treated
with respect by the world's top players," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the start of this year, she made history when she teamed up
with Paradorn to reach the mixed doubles final in the Hopman Cup.
She also enjoyed moderate success in the singles this year by
reaching the third round in the Australian and U.S. Opens and a
fourth round berth in Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
Being modest, she considers herself an unfancied player in the
Olympiad.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone wants to perform her best in the Games, but not
everyone wins. I will be playing in the singles for the first time.
It is going to be as tough as any other professional tournament,"
said Tamarine, the first Thai to play in the Olympics' women's
singles.
</P>
<P>
As regards to doubles specialist Benjamas, 25, she has been
training intensively for the past five months to win qualification,
which will make her the first Thai tennis player to take part in
three Olympiads.
</P>
<P>
She now ranks 165th in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
