<DOCNO> XIE20000910.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rogge: Olympic Games Becomes Too Big and Expensive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Olympic Games was becoming
a logistical nightmare for the hosts and should be scaled back,
said an International Olympic Committee member on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Jacques Rogge said that the Olympics nowsdays can only be
handled by sophisticated cities such as Sydney as many smaller
nations were unable to afford such big-scale floods of personnel
movement and logistical backups.
</P>
<P>
The Games "are still not too big for Sydney or any other big
city of the size, but they are too big for some continents, they
are too big for some sub-continents, and we have to descale them
whilst keeping their quality," Rogge said.
</P>
<P>
So far, Africa, South America, India and China have never
staged an Olympics Games.
</P>
<P>
Rogge, a candidate to succeed Juan Antonio Samaranch as IOC
president, said the Olympics must be made affordable for less
developed regions while still bringing the world's best athletes
to one city.
</P>
<P>
"We'll never spread the Games to different cities because the
value of the Games lies in very simple factors," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's the unity of place -- one city, the unity of time - two
weeks, no more, the unity of action -- all the biggest sports in
the world and the best athletes in the world in the same city at
the same time." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000910.0129 </DOCNO>
