<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain Asks Britain to Repair Its Nuclear Sub in Gibraltar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Spanish Foreign Minister Josep
Pique on Saturday called on the British government to repair its
stricken nuclear-powered Tireless submarine in Gibraltar as soon
as possible.
</P>
<P>
The submarine limped to Gibraltar on May 19, a week after the
discovery of a coolant water leak while it was between Sicily and
the coast of North Africa.
</P>
<P>
Britain promised Spain that the Tireless will leave the port
immediately after repairs, but until now the repairs work has not
started.
</P>
<P>
Britain's procrastination aroused protests and angers in Spain.
Some ecological organizations asked the submarine to get out
immediately and the citizens nearby even asked the authorities to
appeal to the International Court in The Hague. Just two days ago,
the Spanish government called in the British ambassador for a
detailed information of the malfunction.
</P>
<P>
The British side said the sub posed no risk to Gibraltar and
that the British government has coordinated with the Spanish
authorities ever since the troubles happened.
</P>
<P>
Repairs are expected to begin until the safety scrutiny has
been completed and approved. In order to deal with the problem,
Britain and Spain set up a "standing contact group" on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Gibraltar, an area of 5.9 square kilometers, is now the only
colony left on the European continent. It became Spanish territory
in 1501. In 1704, Britain occupied it and turned it into a
military fortress. Spain has long demanded the return of the
strategic "rock" at the gateway from the Atlantic to the
Mediterranean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000910.0142 </DOCNO>
