<HEADLINE> Central American Coffee Exporters Seek to Raise Coffee Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Central American coffee
exporters are seeking an agreement to trade as a block in view of
the low international prices of their product, local media
reported.
</P>
<P>
"It is important to unite our efforts so everybody will pull in
the same direction," Jose Angel Buitrago, chairman of the Central
American Coffee Exporters Organization (Orceca), was quoted as
telling a regional meeting in San Pedro Sula in northern Honduras.
</P>
<P>
Central American producers will start on October 1 to reduce
the output in order to raise the prices, while the reduction has
already been implemented in Brazil and Colombia, Buitrago said.
</P>
<P>
During the San Pedro Sula meeting on Friday, Orceca examined
the market crisis, retention measures and coffee smuggling in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Central America exports some 12 million bags of coffee every
season, while Colombia, the second biggest producer in the world,
exports about 10.5 and 11 million bags. 
</P>
</TEXT>
