<HEADLINE> Clinton Seeks Funding for Forest Fire Prevention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
proposed on Saturday spending about 1.6 billion dollars for the
prevention of forest fires in the country.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the money will help communities recover from
forest fires and also pay for getting rid of forest underbrush to
prevent future blazes.
</P>
<P>
"This excessive undergrowth fuels forest fires, making them far
more dangerous and difficult to control," Clinton said in his
weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
The United States is experiencing one of the worst wildfire
seasons in half a century, with 38 large fires continuing to burn
across nine states.
</P>
<P>
More than 6.6 million acres of forest have been burned so far
in the western states. "I'm committed to working with the
Congress to secure this critical funding," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
He announced the release of nearly 40 million dollars for 90
restoration projects across the West.
</P>
<P>
Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman are expected to meet with western state governors in
Denver next week to discuss cooperative projects for removing
underbrush and small trees. 
</P>
