<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Government Demands FARC Turn Over Hijacker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian government
Saturday demanded the rebel Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia
(FARC) immediately turn over a hijacker to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
A man, being transferred between cities to take part in a
judicial proceeding, hijacked a DASH-300 commuter airliner with
about 20 passengers on board and forced it to land in rebel
territory in the south on Friday, police said.
</P>
<P>
The plane was then allowed to leave immediately and returned to
the central city of Neiva with all the other passengers unharmed.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the incident, the government's high commissioner for
peace, Camilo Gomez, asked the FARC to turn over the hijacker,
identified as Arnobio Ramos Embuz, and avoid causing difficulties
for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The FARC, the biggest guerrilla group in the country, confirmed
the plane landed at the airport in San Vicente del Caguan province,
but denied the hijacker is a member of the guerrilla organization.
</P>
<P>
The hijacker is "a common criminal," FARC spokesman Andres
Paris said. "This was not a guerrilla action, nor a FARC action."
Police said he was a FARC member who killed a police officer.
</P>
<P>
There was no word on whether the FARC would hand over the
hijacker to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
Gomez said the incident was a very unfortunate episode that
needs a prompt solution as it might undermine the fragile peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The San Vicente del Caguan buffer zone was created with the
only purpose of facilitating peace talks between the government
and the FARC, said Gomez adding that the FARC should not use the
buffer zone for any other purposes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
