<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uruguay's Net Foreign Debts Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Uruguayan public
sector's net foreign debts were 2.577 billion U.S. dollars at the
end of June, some 5 percent up over December 1999, according to
official data.
</P>
<P>
This figure is 12.3 percent of the country's gross domestic
product (GDP), compared with 11.6 percent of the GDP at the end of
1999.
</P>
<P>
Factors that caused the debt expansion lay mainly in the non-
financial public sector, whose debts grew 307 million dollars over
this period. The rise is due to the increase in the issuance of
titles in foreign currency and the acquisition of loans from
abroad.
</P>
<P>
The gross foreign debt rise, however, was offset by the
increase of international reserves, together with the rise in
deposits of the residents in foreign currency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
