<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Alerted to Dengue Fever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Costa Rican Health
Ministry Saturday alerted the public to the sharp increase of
dengue fever cases in the country.
</P>
<P>
Public Heath Minister Xinia Carvajal said the number of people
affected by the infectious tropical disease went up from an
average of 8 to 16 per week in the eastern province of Limon.
</P>
<P>
An average of 100 new cases of the disease were reported in the
past weeks in the province of Puntarenas.
</P>
<P>
Health authorities are implementing a preventive campaign to
prevent the spread of the disease, he said.
</P>
<P>
Official data show that two people died of dengue fever and 3,
876 contracted the disease in 1999. The disease is transmitted by
mosquitoes and characterized by severe pains in the joints and
back, fever, and rash.
</P>
<P>
Some 45,000 people have been infected since the disease
appeared in this Central American country at the end of 1993.
</P>
