<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Health News in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are highlights
of major news on health care and medical research in China over
the past week:
</P>
<P>
WFPHA International Congress Opens in Beijing
</P>
<P>
The Ninth International Congress of the World Federation of
Public Health Associations (WFPHA) opened in Beijing on September
2.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,300 participants from 40 countries and regions
attended the five-day congress, which carries the theme of "
Challenges for Public Health at the Dawn of the 21st Century."
</P>
<P>
participants will review the achievements in public health over
the past century and discuss public health problems including the
environment, tobacco control, AIDS prevention, oral and
psychological health in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
 Health Most Important to Chinese in Cyber Age
</P>
<P>
Chinese and people of other Asia-Pacific countries and regions
rate health as the most important thing in their life, according
to the latest survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey done by MasterCard on the consuming trends among
Asians showed that 45 percent of the Asian people polled rated "
health" as the most important aspect to their life.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-one percent of the Chinese surveyed put "health" atop
their list. One in five Chinese chose "family and friends" as the
second most important.
</P>
<P>
The survey was done among 5,447 people from 13 countries and
regions in Asian-Pacific.
</P>
<P>
China to Produce Universal Blood
</P>
<P>
China will begin to manufacture universal blood with the help
of a new technology that turns blood of different types into a
universal one via transgenic engineering, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
The technology has been developed by the Institution of
Transfusion under the Chinese Academy of Military Medicine, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Huayu Group and the Tianjin New Technology Industrial Park
will jointly set up the Huayu Bio-Garden Development Co. Ltd., to
manufacture the blood, with an investment of 240 million yuan (
about 29.3 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The new company will be located in the Torch Venture Garden of
the industrial park in north China's port city of Tianjin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000910.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese Newspapers Keen on Environment Protection Reports
</P>
<P>
Chinese newspapers cover more articles on environmental
protection than before, according to a survey released by a non-
governmental environmental organization "Friends of Nature" on
September 7.
</P>
<P>
The survey covered 75 newspapers, which published 47,000 news
stories on the environment in 1999, or two such stories in one
newspapers each day, compared with one story every two days in
1994.
</P>
<P>
The newspapers devoted a large space to problems on wildlife
protection and air and water pollution last year. However, three
years ago, more environmental reporting was about tree planting,
sanitation and government-advocated environmental campaigns.
</P>
<P>
China Adopts Environment-Friendly Way to Dispose Garbage
</P>
<P>
China is adopting an environment-friendly way of garbage
disposal by building its largest garbage incinerator in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The plant to be built in Shanghai's Pudong New District is
designed to generate 100,000 megawatts of electricity annually by
means of thermal energy generated through burning 365,000 tons of
garbage.
</P>
<P>
The project, expected to be completed in October 2001, will
cost 670 million yuan (80.7 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
China Stresses Closure of Polluting Small Enterprises
</P>
<P>
China will continue to shut down polluting small coal mines,
cement works, oil refineries, steel factories and thermal power
plants despite increasing demand for such products in the country.
</P>
<P>
The State Economic and Trade Commission ordered that
enterprises which failed to meet workplace safety requirements and
contaminated the environment be shut down.
</P>
<P>
Banks will be encouraged not to grant loans to redundant
projects.
</P>
<P>
Administrative means, including power cuts and revoking
operation licenses and permits, will also be employed to ensure
the success of the shut-down drive.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000910.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
