<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Education News in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The following is a review of
major education news Xinhua released on September 3-9:
</P>
<P>
 Prestige Chosen Over Money
</P>
<P>
Although many Chinese colleges promised substantial monetary
prizes for the best performing students in this year's national
college entrance exams, most of these students still chose Qinghua
University and Beijing University, the most prestigious
universities in China.
</P>
<P>
Beijing University enrolled 43 of the top students in the
entrance exams from 23 provinces, municipalities and autonomous
regions, while the Qinghua University recruited 70 percent of the
ten top students for each of the above areas.
</P>
<P>
China's First-Grade Teachers Receive Training
</P>
<P>
Teachers of China's first-grade primary and high school
students were recently trained on the revised teaching materials.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education first trained the administrators,
principals and senior teachers, followed by all other teachers
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The revised books include a compilation of new subject
standards and teaching books, and the revision of current teaching
outlines and books in high schools and the 9-year compulsory
education period.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Higher Education Seekers Realize Dreams
</P>
<P>
More than 73 percent of people seeking higher education in
Beijing were enrolled by colleges and universities this year.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 40,000 students were enrolled, 1,690 more than the
number set beforehand by colleges and universities in the Chinese
capital.
</P>
<P>
Schools with more candidates than ever before have had to
revise their original plan and increased their enrollment quota.
</P>
<P>
To prevent corruption during the course of enrollment, 158
higher education schools have experimented with enrolling students
through the Internet, with 27,000 students enrolled this way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
