<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Following are highlights of
major environment news stories Xinhua released from September 3 to
September 8:
</P>
<P>
Forest Parks Flourish in Guangzhou
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou in south China's Guangdong Province has 16 forest
parks, the biggest number in all provincial capitals in China.
</P>
<P>
As a regional political and economic hub, Guangzhou has forest
covering 41.5 percent of the city area, or 224,000 ha. The city
spends over 10 million yuan (1.2 million US dollars) annually on
tree planting.
</P>
<P>
Local forest parks combine landscape gardens and amusement
grounds with stone-laid walk-ways through woods. The refreshing
environment and convenient infrastructure have made local forest
parks very popular.
</P>
<P>
Germany-Sponsored Forest Project in Northwest China
</P>
<P>
The 20th Germany-sponsored forestation project in China has
been launched in Yan'an, the famous revolutionary base in
northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
With 12 million Deutsche Marks (about 5.5 million U.S. dollars)
from the German government, China will plant 15,700 hectares of
forest and another 2,300 hectares of forest that yields earnings,
and consolidate some 18,000 hectares of farmland in nine years in
Yan'an.
</P>
<P>
China and Germany began to cooperate in forestation eight years
ago. Since then, Germany has donated some 220 million Deutsche
Marks (about 100 million U.S. dollars) to China for forestation
and Germany-aided forests have covered some 100 counties and towns
all over the country.
</P>
<P>
Worsening Environment Calls for Sustained Development
</P>
<P>
The heads of State and government across the world are
gathering in the U.N. headquarters in New York this week to
discuss the major challenges facing the whole mankind in the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
One of the challenges they will discuss is the deteriorating
environment and the strategy of sustained development.
</P>
<P>
The unprecedented development over the past few hundred years
has resulted in the most brilliant civilization of today. But the
price is dear: global warming, water shortage, spreading
desertification and disappearing bio-diversity. The homeland of
mankind is losing its fertility and beauty, a bitter fruit borne
out of an unsustainable way of human activity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000910.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China to Support Development of 11 High-Tech Areas
</P>
<P>
China's Ministry of Science and Technology (MST) has designated
11 high-tech areas for major support, in a bid to push ahead the
development of high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
Top at the list is electronics and information technology.
</P>
<P>
MST officials said the ministry chose those high-tech fields in
accordance with the world science and technology development trend,
and the requirements of China's development strategy of science
and technology as well as economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
Scientist Hopes to Eliminate Hepatitis A in 20 Years
</P>
<P>
China is likely to eliminate hepatitis A in the coming 20 years,
according to a top Chinese scientist.
</P>
<P>
Mao Jiangsen, a professor with the Zhejiang Provincial Academy
of Medical Science, said that in the past decade, more than 100
million Chinese were inoculated with an hepatitis A vaccine.
</P>
<P>
A Better Way to Convert Natural Gas Into Petrochemical
Materials in China
</P>
<P>
China has developed a more efficient way to convert natural gas
into petrochemical materials using microwave catalyzing technology,
opening up a new way to better use of natural gas resources.
</P>
<P>
The technology will increase the one-way C2 hydrocarbon yield
rate to 70 percent from 6 percent in using the traditional method
while the highest yield rate in developed countries is 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
New Auto Emission Purifier Developed in China
</P>
<P>
China has developed the world's first auto emission purifier
using microwave catalyzing technology, which is capable of
rendering the purified emission up to European standard EU2.
</P>
<P>
The purified emission is also very close to EU3, or the next
generation auto emission standard set by the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The purifier was developed by a group of researchers headed by
Dr. Zhang Jinsong, a research fellow at the Institute of Metal
Research, under the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), as one of
the key State-funded research programs between 1996-2000.
</P>
<P>
Long-March 4-B Rocket Succeeds in Three Launches
</P>
<P>
A celebration was held in Shanghai on Sept. 12 for the three
successful launches of Long-March 4-B carrier rocket, which sent a
new earth resource satellite into orbit on September 1.
</P>
<P>
The 45-meter-long rocket, developed by the Shanghai Aerospace
Administration, is an upgraded version of the Long-March 4-A. The
rocket was put into use in May 1999 and has sent four satellites
into space in two pervious launches.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
