<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights
of major science stories released by Xinhua in the past week:
</P>
<P>
New Homepage for China's Top Engineering Body
</P>
<P>
A homepage for the Chinese Academy of Engineering (CAE) has
been put into operation recently after thorough revision and
technological upgrading.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Gaofeng, vice-president of CAE, said the homepage was
designed to act as a window to the operations of CAE, the country'
s top honorary and advisory body in engineering technology.
</P>
<P>
Wildlife May Feint for Entertainment: Scientists
</P>
<P>
Some wild herbivores may enjoy playing with people by "feinting
", according to a group of experts with the Qinhuangdao Safari
Park in north China's Hebei Province, 300 km from Beijing, the
Chiense capital.
</P>
<P>
This safari park, the largest of its kind in China, recorded
the behavior of an "aggressive" male giraffe: it would approach
the visitors voluntarily and kick them lightly with his foreleg
just for fun.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Scientists Set out to Find Yangtze Source
</P>
<P>
An expedition team composed of Chinese scientists and
correspondents set out on Sept. 4 from Guiyang, capital of
southwest China's Guizhou Province, to find the source of the
Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The team will go through Guizhou, Sichuan and Qinghai provinces
and the Tibet Autonomous Region, traveling some 9,000 kilometers
in 60 days.
</P>
<P>
International Seminar on Technical Innovation Opens
</P>
<P>
Officials, researchers and businessmen from over 20 developed
countries gathered in Beijing last week with their Chinese
counterparts to probe possibilities of bilateral or multilateral
cooperation in technological innovations.
</P>
<P>
The International High-Level Seminar on Technological
Innovation focused on building China's national technological
innovation system and drafting policies concerning tax and finance
in advancing technological innovations.
</P>
<P>
China to Expand Cooperation on Major Research Projects
</P>
<P>
China will expand cooperation on major State research and
development projects with overseas research institutes, Zhu Lilan,
Minister of Science and Technology said.
</P>
<P>
Overseas research institutes are welcome to open research and
development centers in China with Chinese counterparts while
Chinese high-tech bodies will also be encouraged to establish
research organs overseas, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Firms Establish Venture to Commercialize Gallium
Arsenide Technology
</P>
<P>
The Institute of Semiconductors with the Chinese Academy of
Sciences (CAS) and four other companies signed an agreement to
commercialize the institute's semi-insulated gallium arsenide
technology.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the agreement will bring about 100 million
to 200 million U.S. dollars in export earnings for China.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Compound Crystal Technology Co., Ltd.
will be set up by the five entities with a registered capital of
100 million yuan (about 12 million U.S. dollars), including
technology valued at 30 million yuan (about 3.6 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
