<HEADLINE> Race Official Killed Accidentally in Italian GP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A young race official died on
Sunday at the Italian Grand Prix held in the Italian northern city
of Monza. He was hit by a wheel which flew into the air during a
multi-car crash at the start of the race.
</P>
<P>
The man, Paolo Gislimberti, 33, was given a heart massage
before being taken by ambulance to Monza hospital.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after arrival, he died of injuries to his head and
chest, police said.
</P>
<P>
Gislimberti was a member of the Monza circuit's volunteer anti-
fire unit, known as 'lions' for the courage they have shown in
emergencies. He was married.
</P>
<P>
"Leave us with our grief," said a woman member of the fire-
fighting group. "Today is a terrible day for us."
</P>
<P>
According to initial reports, it appeared that Gislimberti was
on the wrong side of the guard rail at the side of the track when
he was hit.
</P>
<P>
The Monza prosecutor's office ordered the sequestration of the
Arrows team racing car from which the wheel is believed to have
detached itself during the spectacular cart-wheel crash of Pedro
De La Rosa.
</P>
<P>
In Maranello, home of the Ferrari racing team which won Sunday'
s race, ordered that there be no celebration procession through
the town out of respect for Gislimberti's family. 
</P>
</TEXT>
