<HEADLINE> German Official Still Unsatisfied With OPEC Output Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Berlin, September 10 (Xinhua) -- German Transport Minister
Reinhard Klimmt is still unsatisfied with the latest output
increase of the oil producing countries, according to local press.
</P>
<P>
Klimmt was quoted by "Saarbrueker Zeitung" as saying that he
believed the 800,000 barrels per day increase decided by the
members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC)
will give "certain relief" to soaring oil prices, but its members
"must truly produce more".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Europe-wide protest against high oil prices and
government energy tariffs have also broken out in Germany, as
truck drivers and farmers blockaded towns of Uelzen and Hildesheim,
both in the state of Niedersachsen.
</P>
<P>
The largest-circulated German newspaper Bild reported that the
union of truck drivers threatened to spread the blockade next week
to other cities of the country.
</P>
<P>
The truck drivers demanded lower energy tax, which was
repeatedly rejected by the government. 
