<HEADLINE> British Soldier Killed in Raid in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Britain said on Sunday that
one of its soldiers died and another was seriously injured when
British troops attacked a rebel base in Sierra Leone to free six
British soldiers held hostage.
</P>
<P>
"The Ministry of Defense is able to confirm that one U.K. (
United Kingdom) serviceman was killed in action during this
operation," the defense ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The deceased was dead on arrival at a British ship where the
others were medically examined, the defense ministry said.
</P>
<P>
"One more serviceman is seriously wounded, but his life is not
at risk," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also said that another 11 British soldiers
suffered minor injuries in the raid.
</P>
<P>
"These casualties are regrettable but are at the low end of the
scale for such a difficult and complex operation. Our thoughts are
with the families of all those involved," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Defense ministry officials also said 18 Sierra Leone rebels, 15
men and three women, had been taken prisoner and handed over to
the United Nations, which in turn handed them over to the Sierra
Leonean police.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, British Prime Minister Tony Blair said the British
operation had been "fully successful" and paid tribute to the
skills and professionalism of the armed forces, saying they were
the finest in the world.
</P>
<P>
Speaking outside his Downing Street office a few minutes before
the British soldier's death was announced, Blair said he felt
immense pride in the armed forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
