<HEADLINE> Britain Agrees to Lift Austrian Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"We agree with the report that the measures should be lifted,"
the spokesman said, but adding that Britain was not taking action
unilaterally to lift sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Austria's 14 European Union partners froze bilateral contacts
with Vienna in February, after the far-right Freedom Party, then
led by the controversial Joerg Haider, entered a coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
The EU report, presented last week, said Austria's protection
of the rights of immigrants and minorities was as good as in other
EU countries and in some respects better. It advised that
maintaining the sanctions would be counter-productive.
</P>
<P>
But the report puts French President Jacques Chirac in a
difficult position, as France has been a leading supporter of the
sanctions against Austria.
</P>
<P>
French European Affairs Minister Pierre Moscovici reportedly
said on Sunday that EU countries needed to reach a consensus
before deciding whether to lift sanctions against Austria.
</P>
<P>
Media reports here said Danish Prime Minister Poul Nyrup
Rasmussen said on Sunday he would urge fellow European Union
leaders to end their diplomatic boycott of Austria immediately and
Luxembourg Prime Minister Jean-Claude Juncker has also urged a
quick end to the measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
